text.tspan: A lot of things on this page are just rectangles merged
together. Turns out, it's really hard to make things pixel
perfect at 16x16. Even for simple things like triangles
with 45 degree edges, Inkscape will shift a few pixels here
and there. In the end, I just manually traced shapes with
rectangles to get the pixels right.
I have also tried adding white outlines to the A+B
buttons, which make them stand out better when the
background is all black, but on average they don't
look as nice.
Playdate console images, used to explain the
control scheme for rock/paper/scissors. Two
variants are included here: flat one for rock and
paper, and tilted ones with crank for scissors.
Rocks are done by tilting the console, and the
instruction screen shows the tilt by calling
drawSampled on the flat image. I also tried
baking the tilt images inside Inkscape using live
path effects, but the rasterized results had some
pixel bleeding that I didn't like, so I ended up
doing the tilt at run time.
I always find it strange that "scissors" as a noun
is always plural, so "scissors wins" just doesn't
seem grammatically correct.
These title text are mostly just text converted to paths
with "object to path", except there were a few pixels
around the right parenthesis that rasterized poorly, so
I manually adjusted the curve a bit.
